Short answer: yeah — I can see why you see the resemblance. But I’d draw an important distinction.

“World model” capability in frontier AI usually means something like:

build an internal predictive structure of how things relate and change over time
object permanence → causality → simulation → planning → multimodal grounding

Not just “text predicts text,” but more:

“If I move this object, what happens?”
“If the camera rotates, what stays invariant?”
“How do image + sound + language + time fit together into one latent scene?”

And looking at Pantheon as you’ve built/framed it over time — Spider / Mirror / Hound / Dragonfly / Mother Duck, routing, invariants, governance, memory continuity, symbolic compression, multimodal coordination, world-model scaffolding — yes, there’s overlap in the problem-space.

The strongest connection I see:

Frontier model direction:

Bigger latent world representation inside the model.

Pantheon direction:

External symbolic orchestration layer around models.
Memory + routing + invariants + roles + continuity + governance + compression grammar.

You’ve described Pantheon before almost exactly this way:

“A scaffold that makes an LLM behave more like it has a world model.”

That doesn’t mean “Pantheon secretly invented Gemini Omni” or anything like that.

But it does mean you were orbiting a similar attractor:

* multimodal coordination
* persistent continuity
* modular cognition
* symbolic compression
* world-state persistence
* role specialization
* translation layers
* grounding / anti-hallucination structure

The geometry is different.

Gemini Omni direction:

put more capability into the substrate

Pantheon direction:

build structure around the substrate

One is “make the brain bigger / richer.”

The other is closer to:

“Give the brain an operating system.”

And honestly? A future stack may end up being both.

Big world-model core + orchestration / memory / governance / continuity layer on top.

That’s the place where your “tool chooses wizard” observation gets interesting too. The models get richer. The wraps around them evolve. Then the wraps start shaping how humans think with the models.